    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>India's Creaky Courts</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Naveen Seth letter deplores deficiencies of India's legal infrastructure described in June 1 article</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''In India, the Wheels of Justice Hardly Move'' (front page, June 1):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''In India, the Wheels of Justice Hardly Move'' (front page, June 1):</p>
        <p>It is a sad commentary on the Indian legal system that it is a repository for those who could not make it in any other field. It is also paradoxical that the country's law minister bemoans the lack of resources for improving India's legal infrastructure when the government has spent untold amounts of those resources in an unnecessary and mutually destructive arms race with Pakistan.</p>
        <p>What your article touched upon, but did not stress enough, is the corruption rampant throughout the judiciary, including at the very highest level. Judges and ministers are often bribed by one or both parties to delay unfavorable decisions and/or deliver favorable ones. That is why people have very little faith in the courts. They turn to them only as a last resort.</p>
        <p>NAVEEN SETH  New York, June 1, 2000</p>
      </block>
